ing toward pluralism. Following them over several generations, Rose tracks the experiences of twenty-six interfaith families who recorded their thoughts and feelings in letters, journals, and memoirs. She examines the decisions husbands and wives made about religious commitment, their relationships with the extended families on both sides, and their convictions. These couples--who came from strong Protestant, Catholic, and Jewish backgrounds--did not turn away from religion but made personalized adjustments in religious observance. Increasingly, the author notes, women took charge of religion in the home. Rose's family-centered look at private religious decisions and practice gives new insight on American society in a period when it was becoming more open, more diverse, and less community-bound.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aFamilie. 0aGemengd huwelijk. 0aInterfaith families. 0aInterfaith marriage. 0aJoden. 0aKonfession. 0aMischehe. 0aProtestanten. 0aReligiöse Erziehung. 0aReligiöse Erziehung. 0aRooms-katholieken. 0aSozialwissenschaften, Soziologie, Anthropologie. 4aInterfaith families -- United States -- History -- 19th century. 4aInterfaith marriage -- United States -- History -- 19th century. 4aRELIGION / General. 4aRELIGION / History. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: American History eBook Packagez9783110353464oZDB-23-HAH08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831104422050 cprintz978067442309140uhttps://doi